ly because the Italians considered their way of life suspect. There are uncanny echoes with the situation of the Roma and migrants today. Hom explores three sites, in novella-like essays, where Italy's colonial past touches down in the present: the island, the camp, and the village.Empire's Mobius Strip brings into relief Italy's shifting constellations of mobility and empire, giving them space to surface, submerge, stretch out across time, and fold back on themselves like a Mobius strip. It deftly shows that mobility forges lasting connections between colonial imperialism and neoliberal empire, establishing Italy as a key site for the study of imperial formations in Europe and the Mediterranean.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAlien detention centerszItalyzLampedusa Island. 0aNoncitizen detention centerszItalyzLampedusa Island. 0aRefugeeszItalyzLampedusa Island. 4aHistory. 4aItaly. 4aWest European History.  aAfrica.  aAlgeria.  aAmerican Association of Italian Studies.  aGlobal Politics.  aItaly's current crisis of Mediterranean migration.  aKolonialisme.  aLibya Emigration and immigration.  aMediterranean migrants.  aNoncitizen detention centers.  aalien detention centers italy.  abedouin genocide.  aborder control.  abordering practices.  acampi nomadi.  acontemporary Mediterranean history.  acurrent affairs migrants.  adetention practices.  aemigration studies.  aequipped villages roma.  aeuropean history.  ahistory of italy.  aimmigration studies.  ainfluence of colonialism.  aitalian colonialism.  aitalian ethnographic research.  aitalian genocide.  aitalian history.  aitalian imperialism.  aitalian post colonialism.  aitalian studies.  aitaly carceral islands.  aitaly treatment of migrants.  aitaly's colonial past.  alampedusa isl